{{DYK talk|7 December|2008|entry=... that in [[World War II]], '''[[David M. Jones]]''', later a [[U.S. Air Force]] [[Major General]], participated in events that formed the basis for two [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood movies]]: ''[[Thirty Seconds Over Tokyo]]'' and ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]''?|views=1912}}


==Untitled==
As I recall, upon his retirement on June 1, 1973, General Jones was awarded the Air Force Distinguished Service Medal, which in terms of precedence comes before the Legion of Merit and the DFC. I was an airman assigned to the public affairs office at Patrick AFB at the time. This should probably be added to this article as the source for his decorations was an official USAF biography dated Feb. 1973, prior to his retirement.  <small><span class="autosigned">—Preceding [[Wikipedia:Signatures|unsigned]] comment added by [[User:RZALON|RZALON]] ([[User talk:RZALON|talk]] • [[Special:Contributions/RZALON|contribs]]) 23:31, 27 September 2010 (UTC)</span></small><!-- Template:Unsigned --> <!--Autosigned by SineBot-->

